Author::::MichaelBulley
DateTime::::2016-03-12T08:41:03Z
Heaney falls short, I think, of Virgil’s image in writing “a dream on wings”. That would be, more naturally, “uolucri somnio”, but Virgil writes “somno”, not “somnio”. It is rare for “somnus” to mean a dream and I don’t think it does here. Virgil is saying that the ghost of Anchises slips though Aeneas’s hands “like winged sleep”.



