Author::::Idowu Omoyele
DateTime::::2016-03-11T22:16:13Z
Seamus Heaney was born near Castledawson, County Derry in Northern Ireland on 13 April, 1939, the year W.B. Yeats died. Yeats remains the greatest of all Irish poets and, with T.S. Eliot, the most iconic and influential modernist poet in English. Although the American poet Robert Lowell esteemed him as "the most important Irish poet since Yeats," Heaney may look back more to Wordsworth than to Yeats in terms of affinity and influence, while he also engaged with and learnt from poets from eastern Europe like the Pole Czeslaw Milosz. By 1995, when he received the Nobel Prize for Literature "for works of lyrical beauty and ethical depth, which exalt everyday miracles and the living past," Heaney had already become one of the greatest poets of the postwar period and, with Derek Walcott and Christopher Okigbo, one of the three most distinguished poets to appear in English during the 1960s. By the time of his death in Dublin, Republic of Ireland on 30 August 2013, having suffered a stroke in 2006, he had already created the most remarkable body of work by any poet to emerge from the British Isles since the Second World War. Yes, he once bristled at being included in an anthology of British poetry with this poetically expressed quip:



