Author::::LithophaneFurcifera
DateTime::::2016-03-11T21:27:20Z
But Aeneas is not so much a refugee (he didn't flee from the Trojan War, he fought in it, only making his escape when Troy was defeated) as a colonist, founding Lavinium which would later become Rome (and thereby providing a grand origin myth for the city, along with that of Romulus and Remus), despite local opposition and conflict with the Rutuli. If he were merely looking for safety, he could have lived quite happily ever after with Dido in Cathage, instead of leading her on and subsequently shafting her in favour of the "manifest destiny" that led him onwards to Hesperia [lit. the Western land, i.e. the Italian peninsula].



